<article>
    <h1>THE GER&#xAD;ALD GENTA ARENA BI-RET&#xAD;RO&#xAD;GRADE SPORT</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200911/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-09-11"><time>2020-09-11</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>The late Ger­ald Genta has de­signed some of the world’s most iconic watches, in­clud­ing the Royal Oak for Audemars Piguet and the Nau­tilus for Patek Philippe.</p>
    <p>The Swiss also came up with some funky time­pieces un­der his own brand, which was bought by Bvlgari in 2000.</p>
    <p>Bvlgari has de­cided to breathe new life into the Genta legacy with the Arena Bi-Ret­ro­grade Sport (above).</p>
    <p>With its arena case in­spired by the glad­i­a­to­rial am­phithe­atres of an­cient Rome, the watch has a jump­ing hour win­dow at 12 o’clock with a minute track along the top half of the dial.</p>
    <p>The date track is on the bot­tom half. It is fit­ted with the BVL 300 move­ment, which sees the minute hand snap­ping back to zero every 60 min­utes and the date snap­ping back every 31 days.</p>
    <p>Priced at $20,800, the watch has a ti­ta­nium case and a dis­play back show­cas­ing the in­tri­ca­cies of the BVL 300.</p>

